  "text": "Since the total transition probability is proportional to the dynamic floor field it becomes more attractive to follow in the footsteps of other pedestrians. This effect competes with the preferred walking direction specified by M ij and the effects of the geometry encoded in S ij . The relative influence of the contributions (i)-(iii) is controlled by coupling parameters. These depend on the situation to be studied. Consider for example a situation where people want to leave a large room (see [CITATION_1] ). Normal circumstances, where everybody is able to see the exit, can be modelled by solely using a static floor field which decreases radially with the distance from the door. Since transitions in the direction of larger fields are more likely this will automatically guarantee that everybody is walking in the direction of the door. If, however, the exit can not be seen by everybody, e.g. in a smoke-filled room or in the case of failing lights, people will try to follow others hoping that they know the location of the exit. In this case the coupling to the dynamic floor field is much stronger and the static field has a considerable influence only in the vicinity of the door. This example will be studied in more detail in [CITATION_2] .",
